The code statements that lead to the bug are:
```java
StringBuilder location = new StringBuilder(request.getRequestURI());
location.append('/');
```
Reason:
The code constructs a redirect URL by appending a forward slash to the request URI. If the request URI already contains a leading slash, this can result in a protocol-relative URL (e.g., "//example.com/"), which can lead to incorrect URL resolution depending on the context.

The code statements that fix the bug are:
```java
while (location.length() > 1 && location.charAt(1) == '/') {
    location.deleteCharAt(0);
}
```
Reason:
This code checks if the constructed URL has a leading double slash and removes the first character if it does. This ensures that the redirect URL is properly formatted, avoiding the generation of a protocol-relative redirect and ensuring correct navigation for users.

